The Howling Cairn
(Internal Title: This adventure will be referred to as "The Silver Cairn" in all player-facing text)
A Skyrim One-Shot Adventure for 4 Players (Adept Tier)
Estimated Play Time: 2-3 hours
Party Size: 4 players
Difficulty: Adept Tier (3 AP each)
Reward: 1,400 gold per player, powerful enchanted items, and 1 AP

Adventure Summary
A wealthy Nord family's ancestral tomb, the Silver Cairn, has been desecrated by a group of rogue College mages. The Silverblood family hired mercenaries to clear it out—but they haven't returned. Now they're hiring the party as a backup plan. The twist: Ylva the Cleaver, a boisterous werewolf butcher, has been hunting these necromancers as "worthy prey" and will crash into the dungeon halfway through, her joyous hunting howls having been mistaken for a monstrous threat.

City Profile Stub: Markarth
High Concept: A city of stone and secrets, carved into a mountain over the bones of a dead Dwemer civilization, ruled by the iron-fisted and paranoid Silver-Blood clan.
Atmosphere: The air tastes of stone dust and metal, and the constant roar of waterfalls echoes through the stone canyons of the city. There is a pervasive sense of being underground even when outdoors, a claustrophobia that breeds suspicion.
Core Conflict: "Wealth vs. Blood." The Silver-Bloods control the lucrative silver mines that are the city's lifeblood, but the native Reachmen (the Forsworn) believe the land is theirs by ancient right. This creates a constant, simmering tension and a brutal approach to justice.

Part I: The Silver-Blood Manor
The Hook: A Transaction of Honor
Read Aloud:
"You are escorted through the cavernous stone halls of Understone Keep, the seat of power in Markarth. The air is cool and smells of damp stone and hot metal from the forges. Unlike the wooden warmth of Whiterun, everything here is unyielding stone, carved and shaped by hands long dead. Armed guards in the Silver-Blood livery watch you pass, their faces as hard and grey as the walls around them.
You are shown into a private study, a room of surprising Nord austerity amidst the Dwemer grandeur. Animal pelts cover the floor, and weapons of Nordic steel adorn the walls. Behind a grand oak desk sits Thongvor Silver-Blood, a man whose stern face and powerful build mark him as a true son of the Reach. He does not rise. He simply gestures to the chairs before him, his eyes assessing you like a blacksmith judging a piece of iron.
He pushes a heavy, jingling purse of gold across the desk. It clinks to a stop before you.
'Fourteen hundred gold each,' he says, his voice a low growl like grinding stone. 'My family's tomb—the Silver Cairn—has been occupied by College dropouts playing with corpses. An infestation. I sent six good men three days ago to handle it. They haven't come back. Now I am sending professionals.'
He leans forward, his gaze hardening. 'Clear out the tomb. Bring me proof the necromancers are dead—their heads, their robes, I don't care. End the nightly howling that dishonors my ancestors. The gold is yours. Are there any questions, or are you ready to do the job you were hired for?'"
GM's Toolkit: Roleplaying Thongvor Silver-Blood
Demeanor: Pragmatic, impatient, and utterly convinced of his own authority. He is not a king asking for aid; he is a wealthy industrialist hiring exterminators. Every moment spent talking is a moment the job isn't getting done. He respects strength and results, nothing else.
Physical Presence: He remains seated for the entire meeting, a subtle power move. His hands are calloused and strong, resting on the desk. He maintains direct, unblinking eye contact.
Key Dialogue Prompts:
If asked about the first mercenaries: "Six men from the Reach. Good fighters, but not specialists. I paid them half up front. Now they're a sunk cost—either dead or cowards who fled with my coin. It makes no difference to me. Their failure is why you're here."
If asked about the necromancers: "At least three of them, from what my scouts saw. An Altmer, a Dunmer, and a Breton. College robes. They're amateurs, dabblers who think they can defile a Silver-Blood tomb and get away with it. They are mistaken."
If asked about the "howling": His jaw tightens. "It started two weeks ago. A sound that carries on the wind every night. It's not a wolf's howl. Deeper. More... resonant. It sounds like the mountain itself is groaning in pain. A desecration. My ancestors were hunters who met their end with a roar, not a whimper. I want it silenced."
If the party tries to negotiate: He scoffs. "The price is the price. It is more than generous. Do the job, and you get paid. Fail, and you'll be another cautionary tale I tell the next group I hire. Now, are we done here?"


What Thongvor Provides
The Contract: A signed letter bearing the Silver-Blood seal, granting official authorization to clear the cairn. Payment of 1,400 gold per person upon completion.
The Location: A map marking the Silver Cairn, a 90-minute trek northeast into the hills of the Reach.
The Intel: Three rogue mages (Altmer, Dunmer, Breton) are the primary targets. The six mercenaries sent before them are missing and presumed dead. An unnatural howling emanates from the area nightly.

Part II: The Approach
Environmental Escalation: The Howling
The journey into the Reach is stark and beautiful, but as the party nears the location on the map, the atmosphere changes.
Read Aloud:
"The landscape of the Reach is a jagged tapestry of grey stone and hardy green pines. The path to the cairn is steep and unforgiving. About fifteen minutes out from the marked location, you hear it for the first time. A low, vibrating hum that rises slowly into a mournful, guttural howl. It seems to come from the stones themselves, a sound that raises the hair on your arms. The air grows cold, and the scent of rot seems to thicken beneath the smell of pine."
GM's Note: The howling is, in fact, Ylva's joyous hunting cries, distorted and made to sound ancient and mournful by the echoing canyons and the tomb's stone structure. She is actively hunting the necromancers' minions in the hills around the cairn.
The Warning: A Forensic Investigation
At the entrance to the tomb, the party finds a grim tableau.
Read Aloud:
"The Silver Cairn squats on a hillside like a wounded animal. The ancient Nordic structure is half-collapsed, its stone entrance framed by dead trees that look like skeletal hands clawing at the sky. The howling is louder here.
At the entrance lie the first three bodies of the missing mercenaries. They have not been left where they fell. They have been arranged in a deliberate circle, posed in a mockery of prayer, facing the tomb's dark entrance. Their eyes are missing, and their mouths are frozen shut. Carved into each forehead is a glowing, sickly green rune."
Investigation Opportunity (Clue Web)
This forensic scene provides critical tactical intelligence about the threats ahead.
The Runes (Standard Magic Roll): The runes are Daedric in origin, but the grammar is sloppy. Tactical Clue: The necromancers are arrogant and likely overconfident, but not masters of their craft.
The Wounds (Standard Guile Roll): The bodies are unnaturally desiccated, their life force drained but their armor seems completely untouched. Tactical Clue: The mages within rely on magic that bypasses physical armor.
The Beast's Mark (Hard (-2) Guile Roll): A character examining the ground finds something that creates a compelling contradiction. They find massive paw prints, far too large for any normal wolf, pressed deep into the earth. They are fresh. One of the posed bodies has fresh wounds like it had been disturbed after it was arranged—it has been partially mauled, as if by a large predator that was interrupted while scavenging. The Mystery: The party now has two conflicting pieces of evidence: the sound of a mournful, ethereal howling, and the physical tracks of a very real, very large beast. What kind of monster is haunting this cairn?
The Note (Automatic Discovery): Tucked into the fist of one mercenary is a blood-stained note: "Turn back. The honored dead have new masters now." This confirms the necromancers' arrogance.
GM Note: The party is now walking into a situation with more tension and mystery. They face arrogant mages who use drain spells, and they have confirmed the presence of a powerful, unidentified beast that seems hostile to everyone.

Part III: The Cairn Interior - A Streamlined Dungeon
GM's Note on Pacing: This dungeon is designed for a fast-paced, action-oriented session. It has four chambers instead of the standard five. Each encounter is a distinct tactical challenge. Encourage forward momentum and decisive action.

Chamber 1: The Defiled Antechamber
Read Aloud:
"You step through the ancient stone archway into the Silver Cairn. The air is immediately colder, thick with the smell of churned earth, ozone, and a cloying, chemical scent of decay that is nothing like natural rot. The howling you heard outside is muffled, but the low, vibrating hum still resonates through the stone floor.
The entrance hall is a scene of methodical desecration. Ancient burial alcoves, carved with the names of long-dead Silver-Blood warriors, have been forced open. Their contents—brittle bones, rusted weapons, and tarnished grave goods—are scattered across the floor in a chaotic mess.
At the far end of the chamber, four skeletal warriors stand in a silent, disciplined line. Their rusted Nordic armor is fused to their bones, and their hollow eye sockets burn with sickly green light. Behind this grim shield wall, a robed figure—a young, panicked-looking Breton—gestures frantically, his hands crackling with the same green energy that animates his guardians. He sees you, and his face twists with fear and anger. 'You are not welcome here! These dead are ours!'"
Encounter: The Novice Necromancer & Skeletal Guard
This is a straightforward tactical challenge designed to test the party's ability to break a defensive formation.
