Tactics
The Controller (Altmer): She sees the party's melee fighters as the greatest threat to the ritual. She will use Paralyze to lock down the most dangerous-looking warrior, then use Chain Lightning to damage multiple targets at once. Her goal is to buy time by disabling the party.
The Artillery (Dunmer): He is focused on raw destruction. He will open with Blizzard to damage the entire party and create difficult terrain, then summon a Frost Atronach to act as a bodyguard and tie up melee attackers.
Synergy: The necromancers will coordinate their attacks, with the Altmer paralyzing targets to make them easy prey for the Dunmer's Blizzard and the Atronach's slam attacks. They will ignore anyone trying to free the mercenaries, believing their magic is superior to such "mundane" efforts.
Environmental Hazard
Necrotic Pulse: At the end of each round, the incomplete ritual releases a wave of dark energy. Every living creature in the room (including the party but excluding the necromancers) takes 2 irreducible necrotic damage.
Loot & Clues
Ring of Necromancy: Worn by the Dunmer. This polished bone ring allows the wearer to cast Raise Zombie once per day (0 FP).
Staff of Ice Storms: Held by the Altmer. This gnarled yew staff is topped with a flawless, fist-sized chunk of ice. It allows the user to cast Ice Storm once per day.
Research Notes:The notes are written in a precise, elegant, and chillingly detached script: "Subject: Lucien. The Breton's command of raw necromantic force is undeniable—a true prodigy. His 'apotheosis' ritual to become a 'Bone God' is theoretically sound, if suicidally arrogant. My calculations place the probability of catastrophic failure at approximately 47%.
In such an event, the resulting surge of raw soul-energy from the collapsing rift will be more than sufficient to power our soul-funnel to the Soul Cairn for a full century.
If he succeeds, I am the vizier to a god. If he fails, I inherit his power. Both outcomes are acceptable."
Alchemical Pouch: On the Dunmer's belt is a pouch containing 400 gold and 3 Potions of Greater Healing.
Rescued Mercenaries
If saved, the mercenaries are unconscious but stable. As the party is stabilizing them after the fight, one will stir, his eyes wide with feverish terror. He'll grab a party member's arm and gasp: "The Breton... in the burial vault... he's… he's trying to build a god..." before passing out again.




Part IV: The Howling Cairn Interior
Chamber 3: The Hall of Dishonor
The passage from the Ritual Chamber leads down a short, dark corridor to a large, ceremonial hall.
Read Aloud:
"The corridor opens into a long, vaulted hallway that feels far more grand than the crude chambers you have passed through. This is a ceremonial hall of honor. Suits of pristine, ancient Nordic armor stand in alcoves along the walls, their steel gleaming with faint enchantments. Banners bearing the Silver-Blood crest, miraculously preserved, hang from the ceiling.
At the far end of the hall stands a massive, circular door of polished obsidian, humming with a palpable magical energy. But it is not unguarded.
Standing before the door is another robed necromancer, this one a gaunt Altmer with a cruel sneer. Flanking him are two spectral warriors, their forms a swirling vortex of bound souls and ethereal armor, their empty eye sockets burning with the cold light of the Soul Cairn. They are the honored dead of the Silver-Blood line, their spirits torn from Sovngarde and twisted into unwilling guardians.
The Altmer necromancer sees you and laughs, a high, mocking sound. 'More insects for the collection. You are too late. He is nearly ready. You will have the honor of being the first souls to feed our new gateway!'
As he speaks, the ancestral spirits raise their spectral blades and glide towards you. Roll for initiative."
